# SmartBook MCQ Solver — Fast-Chain Mode

Answers McGraw-Hill SmartBook questions at maximum speed using a single
chained JavaScript call per question: **read → select → High confidence →
Next**, no screenshots, no verification pauses between questions.

At the end, output a compact answer-key table — answers only, no question
re-statement.

---

## Step 0 — Access McGraw-Hill Connect

### 0a — Get the active tab

```javascript
// Use tabs_context_mcp to get the current tab group.
// If no group exists, create one with createIfEmpty: true.
tabs_context_mcp({ createIfEmpty: true })
```

### 0b — Navigate to Connect and login

#### 0b-i — Search for McGraw-Hill Connect login

Type `mcgrawhill connect login` into the browser address/search bar and navigate:

```javascript
navigate(tabId, "mcgrawhill connect login")
// Wait 3 seconds for search results to load
```

Click the **first search result link** that appears.

Wait 3 seconds for the page to load, then check `document.title` and `location.href`.

**Decision logic:**

| Page title / URL | Situation | Action |
|------------------|-----------|--------|
| Contains "Connect Student UI" or dashboard visible | Already logged in | Go to Step 0c immediately |
| Login page loaded | Credentials needed | Run Step 0b-ii (click red Sign In button) |

#### 0b-ii — Trigger autofill via real user gesture, then submit

Chrome's password manager only autofills after a real user interaction on the input fields. Use the `computer` tool to perform actual mouse clicks on the email and password fields — this triggers Chrome's native autofill. Then click the Sign In button.

**Phase 1 — Trigger autofill with real mouse clicks**

Use `computer` tool (mouse click) to:
1. Click the email/username input field — wait 1.5 s for Chrome autofill dropdown to appear
2. Press the **Down arrow key** once to select the saved credential from the dropdown, then press **Enter** to confirm — wait 1 s
3. If the password field is not auto-populated after step 2, click the password field and repeat the Down + Enter gesture — wait 1 s

> **Do not type anything.** The goal is purely to simulate a real user click so Chrome injects saved credentials. If no autofill dropdown appears after clicking (field stays empty), fall through to Phase 2.

**Phase 2 — Verify fields are populated**

```javascript
(async () => {
  const d = ms => new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, ms));
  await d(800);
  const emailField = document.querySelector('input[type="email"], input[name*="email"], input[name*="user"], input[id*="email"], input[id*="user"]');
  const passField  = document.querySelector('input[type="password"]');
  return JSON.stringify({
    emailFilled: !!(emailField && emailField.value.length > 0),
    passFilled:  !!(passField  && passField.value.length  > 0),
    emailVal:    emailField ? emailField.value.substring(0, 30) : 'not found',
  });
})()
```

| Result | Action |
|--------|--------|
| Both `true` | Proceed to Phase 3 (click Sign In) |
| Either `false` | Fields still empty — use `computer` tool to click each empty field once more, wait 2 s, re-run Phase 2 check; if still empty after 2 tries, take screenshot and ask user to click the email field themselves so Chrome autofill activates, then resume |

**Phase 3 — Click Sign In and verify login (10-attempt retry loop)**

```javascript
(async () => {
  const d = ms => new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, ms));

  function isLoggedIn() {
    return (
      document.title.toLowerCase().includes('connect') &&
      !location.href.includes('accounts.mheducation')
    ) || document.title.toLowerCase().includes('connect student ui');
  }

  function findRedSignInBtn() {
    const byText = [...document.querySelectorAll('button, input[type="submit"]')]
      .find(b =>
        b.innerText?.toLowerCase().includes('sign in') ||
        b.value?.toLowerCase().includes('sign in')
      );
    if (byText) return byText;

    const byRole = [...document.querySelectorAll('[role="button"]')]
      .find(b => b.innerText?.toLowerCase().includes('sign in'));
    if (byRole) return byRole;

    const byAnchor = [...document.querySelectorAll('a')]
      .find(a => a.innerText?.toLowerCase().includes('sign in'));
    if (byAnchor) return byAnchor;

    const byAttr = document.querySelector(
      '[data-testid*="sign"], [id*="signin"], [id*="login"], [class*="signin"], [class*="login-btn"]'
    );
    if (byAttr) return byAttr;

    return null;
  }

  await d(1000);

  let attempt = 0;
  const MAX = 10;

  while (attempt < MAX) {
    attempt++;

    if (isLoggedIn()) {
      return JSON.stringify({ status: 'logged_in', attempt, title: document.title, url: location.href });
    }

    const btn = findRedSignInBtn();

    if (btn) {
      try {
        btn.click();
      } catch (e) {
        btn.dispatchEvent(new MouseEvent('click', { bubbles: true, cancelable: true }));
      }
    } else {
      window.scrollBy(0, 300);
    }

    const waitMs = attempt <= 3 ? 3000 : attempt <= 6 ? 4000 : 5000;
    await d(waitMs);

    if (isLoggedIn()) {
      return JSON.stringify({ status: 'logged_in', attempt, title: document.title, url: location.href });
    }
  }

  return JSON.stringify({
    status: 'failed_after_10_attempts',
    title: document.title,
    url: location.href,
    bodySnippet: document.body.innerText.substring(0, 600)
  });
})()
```

**Interpreting the result:**

| `status` | Next action |
|----------|-------------|
| `"logged_in"` | Proceed to Step 0c immediately |
| `"failed_after_10_attempts"` | Check `bodySnippet` — if CAPTCHA present, tell user once and wait; if the page shows a university SSO page, wait an extra 15 s and retry the whole loop once more; otherwise screenshot and report to user |

> **Only stop for CAPTCHA or bot-detection.** If a CAPTCHA appears, tell the
> user once: "A CAPTCHA appeared — please solve it and I'll continue." Resume
> as soon as they confirm. For all other scenarios, retry automatically.

