## Subject-Matter Quick Reference — Ch. 19: Third-Party Rights

| Concept | Answer pattern |
|---------|----------------|
| Transfer of **rights** | Assignment |
| Transfer of **duties** | Delegation |
| Receives rights | Assignee |
| Gives away rights | Assignor |
| Receives duties | Delegatee |
| Gives away duties | Delegator |
| Assignor after assignment | **No rights left** |
| Delegator after delegation | **Still liable** if delegatee fails |
| Personal-service contract | Non-assignable AND non-delegable |
| Poorly-worded antiassignment clause | Unenforceable → assignment valid |
| Right to receive **payment** | Always assignable even with antiassignment clause |
| Obligor defenses after assignment | Survive — assertable against assignee |
| Why assignee gives notice | So obligor knows **who to perform for** |
| First-assignment-in-time (majority US) | First assignee in time wins |
| English rule (minority US) | First to give **notice** wins |
| Ambiguous "I assign the contract" | Court treats as **both rights AND duties** |
| Intended beneficiary | Contract's purpose = benefit them; enforceable rights |
| Incidental beneficiary | Unintended benefit; **no** enforceable rights |
| Donee beneficiary | Benefits from a **gift** promise |
| Creditor beneficiary | Contract meant to **discharge a debt** owed to them |
| Promisor | Makes the promise benefiting third party |
| Promisee | Owes promisor consideration in exchange |
| Rights un-blockable by antiassignment clause | Right to receive payment; right to receive breach damages |
| Non-delegable duties | Personal in nature; contractually forbidden |
| Non-assignable rights | Personal; prohibited by contract; prohibited by law |
| Vesting of beneficiary rights | Assents, brings suit, or materially relies |
| Donee beneficiary definition T/F | **TRUE** — benefits from gift promise |
| Delegator relieved after delegation T/F | **FALSE** — delegator stays liable |
| Swapped donee/creditor definitions T/F | **FALSE** — definitions are reversed in the question |
